First, I read the table and initiate a blank canvas on which to put my plot.


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
weather <- read_csv("data/weather_data.csv")
```

::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr}

```
Rows: 9 Columns: 10
── Column specification ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Delimiter: ","
chr  (3): station_id, weather_condition, wind_direction
dbl  (6): temperature_c, humidity_pct, wind_speed_kmh, pressure_hpa, precipi...
dttm (1): observation_time

ℹ Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
ℹ Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.
```


:::

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(weather)
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](01-04_complex_variables_plotting_files/figure-html/initiate_plot-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::



### Adding axes
We use another function, `aes`, as an argument to the `ggplot` function,  telling R how various attributes of the data map to the "aesthetics" of the plot.

For example, here we choose which data we will represent with the *x* and *y* axes.


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(weather, aes(
  x = observation_time,
  y = temperature_c
))
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](01-04_complex_variables_plotting_files/figure-html/axes_plot-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::


### Adding Data

Now we can add some data to our graph. In this plotting package, `ggplot`, we add additional things to our plot using a `+` symbol.

Here, we add a line representing the data using the `geom_line` function.


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(weather, aes(
  x = observation_time,
  y = temperature_c
)) +
  geom_line()
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](01-04_complex_variables_plotting_files/figure-html/line_plot-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::


### Adding extra features

We can add some additional features here to make the plot look nicer. For example, here I will change the colour of the line to red, add *x* and *y* axis labels and add a title.


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
ggplot(weather, aes(
  x = observation_time,
  y = temperature_c
)) +
  geom_line(color = "red") +
  xlab("Date") +
  ylab("Temp (C)") +
  ggtitle("Temperature by Date")
```

::: {.cell-output-display}
![](01-04_complex_variables_plotting_files/figure-html/colour_line_plot-1.png){width=672}
:::
:::


